From looking at the regular plot without it being filled, we can see that theres a large proportion of people over 25 years old that have a bachelors degree or higher. From the regular plot, it looks like white alone has the highest number of people with bachelors degrees. Although this may be true, when we see the filled plot and look at white alone for bachelors degree and some college or associates degree, we can see that there is the same proportion of white alone households that have bachelors and associates/some college. This shows the significance of having multiple avenues for data visualization for the same data! In addition to this observation, for the some other race alone, I am assuming they are minorities not included in the five main categories. It looks like for some other race alone, there is a smaller proportion of educational attainment as degrees increase. This is interesting because it is completely opposite of the two or more races category. Although the numbers are lower, their educational attainment proportion increases as the education increases (with a slight dip between associates/some college vs.bachelors). For most of these race categories, we can see that the maximum proportion is usually for some college/associates degree which is expected as the age for this data is 25 and above - people merely arent done with their education or they are taking a break/have other priorities before continuing their education. If this had an age 40+ cutoff, that would be cool to see how many people pursue their GED, Associates, or Bachelors later in life!
